[normal]BNI0027[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Written evidence submitted by HM Government[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Summary:[bold]&#xa0;[bold]The Government welcomes the Committee’s examination of this important issue. We recognise the significant challenges that the banking sector in 
[normal]Northern Ireland
[normal] faces, and we are determined to work closely with the Northern Ireland Executive to help to boost bank lending to businesses. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The framework the UK Government and Northern Ireland Executive set out in our 
[normal]Building a Prosperous and United Community
[normal] document, announced on 14 June, sets out initiatives in this area and outlines an ongoing mechanism for addressing banking and access to finance issues in 
[normal]Northern Ireland
[normal]. The Government’s evidence below covers each of the seven topics highlighted by the Committee. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal](i)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The structure and governance of banks in [bold]Northern Ireland[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]There are clearly significant differences in the banking structure in 
[normal]Northern Ireland
[normal] compared to Great Britain (GB). Of the four main banks – 
[normal]Ulster
[normal], First Trust, Bank of Ireland and 
[normal]Danske
[normal] – three are not UK-owned. First Trust (as part of Allied Irish Banks) and Bank of Ireland are headquartered in 
[normal]Dublin
[normal], whilst 
[normal]Danske
[normal] is Danish-owned. Some large GB banks such as HSBC and Barclays only have a comparatively small presence in 
[normal]Northern Ireland
[normal]. The strong link between the banking system in 
[normal]Northern Ireland
[normal] and the 
[normal]Republic
[normal] of 
[normal]Ireland
[normal] presents particular challenges, given the difficulties faced by the Irish economy in recent years. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The Chancellor has made clear that the link between our financial systems, which is most pronounced in 
[normal]Northern Ireland
[normal], was a strong factor in the Government’s decision to provide a bilateral loan to the 
[normal]Republic
[normal] of 
[normal]Ireland
[normal].  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The 
[normal]UK
[normal] signed an agreement for a bilateral loan of £3.2 billion in December 2010, as part of an €67.5 billion international financial assistance package for 
[normal]Ireland
[normal]. The 
[normal]Government expects the loan to be repaid in full and with interest.  
[normal]Sweden
[normal] and 
[normal]Denmark
[normal] have also provided bilateral loans to 
[normal]Ireland
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The loan is disbursed in eight tranches of £4
[normal]03 
[normal]million, subject to the completion of quarterly programme reviews. The first seven tranches have been disbursed to date.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The conditions of the bilateral loan also made clear that the funding was subject to the Iri
[normal]sh Government not amending its r
[normal]estr
[normal]ucturing p
[normal]lan in a way that would have a material adverse financial impact on the 
[normal]UK
[normal] operations of Anglo Irish bank, Allied Irish Banks or the Bank of Ireland. 
[normal] 
[normal]As the Chancellor 
[normal]said when the Loans to Ireland Act was debated in the House of Commons
[normal], providing the bilateral loan has enabled 
[normal]the Government
[normal] to be part of discussions about the restructuring plan and its impact on the UK subsidiaries of banks which have significant presence in Northern Ireland.
[normal]The National Asset Management Agency (NAMA) 
[normal]is one of 
[normal]a number of initiatives taken by the Irish Government to address the crisis in Irish banking. 
[normal]NAMA was formally established on 21 December 2009. Five institutions (and their subsidiaries) applied to join the NAMA scheme and were designated as participating institutions in February 2010: Allied Irish Banks; Bank of Ireland; Anglo Irish Bank; Irish Nationwide Building Society; and EBS Building Society.
[normal]The first phase of NAMA’s operation involved the acquisition and transfer of over €71 billion in loan assets involving 850 debtors and more than 11,000 individual loans collateralised by 16,000 individual properties. Approximately two-thirds of the assets backing those loans are located in 
[normal]Ireland
[normal] and most of the remainder is located in the 
[normal]UK
[normal] with smaller concentrations in the 
[normal]US
[normal] and throughout continental 
[normal]Europe
[normal].
[normal]On the proposal of the Irish Minister for Finance, NAMA set up a Northern Ireland Advisory Committee. Its purpose is to advise the Board in relation to strategy for 
[normal]Northern Ireland
[normal] assets. 
[normal]Approximately 3
[normal] per cent 
[normal]of NAMAs property profile is 
[normal]located in Northern Ireland; 36 per cent
[normal] Dublin; 18
[normal] per cent
[normal] Rest of Ireland; 21
[normal] per cent London; 12 per cent
[normal] Rest of GB; and 10
[normal] per cent
[normal] Rest of World.
[normal]Its portfolio i
[normal]n NI is worth €1.3 billion or 4 per cent 
[normal]of its total acquisition value of
[normal] €31.8billion. Approximately 70 per cent
[normal] of its NI portfolio is completed property and income producing. By 
[normal]the end of 
[normal]March 2013, asset sales approved stood at £86.6 million. By the same time, it had approved £123 million in new advances to NI debtors.
[normal] NAMAs stated approach has been to encourage a phased and orderly realisation of its assets in 
[normal]Northern Ireland
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
