[normal]              
[normal]The possible break[bold]-[bold]up of RBS/Ulster Bank[bold] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The Government recognises that RBS, including Ulster Bank, remains weighed down by too many poor assets. The Chancellor announced in his Mansion House speech on 19 June that the Treasury would be examining the case for breaking RBS up and establishing a Bad Bank.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The Government welcomed the input of the Northern Ireland Executive on the future of RBS, conveyed through its former and current finance ministers, Sammy Wilson and Simon Hamilton. The views of the 
[normal]Northern Ireland
[normal] business community were also considered following on from representations by the Secretary of State for 
[normal]Northern Ireland
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]On 1 November 2013, RBS announced that it was committing to a new direction for the bank, in order for it to restructure and boost the British and Irish economies. RBS 
[normal]will 
[normal]create an internal 
[normal]bad bank 
[normal]and £9 billion of Ulster Bank assets will be transferred into this new structure.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The Chancellor recently stated that the Government, RBS and the Bank of England are all in agreement on the direction that RBS is heading. 
[normal]RBS will focus on its core 
[normal]UK
[normal] business
[normal]. 
[normal]It will sell off more of its overseas operations and 
[normal]continue to reduce 
[normal]its investment bank, so it has more capital to support lending to the 
[normal]UK
[normal] economy. RBS 
[normal]has also committed
[normal] to becoming the best small business bank in 
[normal]the 
[normal]UK
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]RBS’s operations in 
[normal]Northern Ireland
[normal] 
[normal]through Ulster Bank, which also operates in 
[normal]Ireland
[normal],
[normal] remain an important part of RBS’s core operations and the new direction the 
[normal]bank has announced. However, a sustainable operating model needs to be found for it so that it can play its full part in delivering 
[normal]support to both economies
[normal]. To achieve this, RBS has announced that Ulster Bank will be part of 
[normal]its full business review, reporting
[normal] in February 2014, with the aim of identifying a long term viable and sustainable business model
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]It is in the 
[normal]UK
[normal]’s interest that 
[normal]Ireland
[normal] has a successful economy and a stable banking system. 
[normal]It is therefore important that Ulster Bank is in a position to support the economy in both 
[normal]Northern Ireland
[normal] 
[normal]and 
[normal]the 
[normal]Republic
[normal] of 
[normal]Ireland
[normal], through new lending and generating new business.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]RBS's 1st November announcement is a positive step in this direction since it will see Ulster Bank remain as an important part of the RBS group, with its balance sheet strengthened by the transfer of problem assets to the internal bad bank. Developing a sustainable business model for Ulster Bank which is capable of
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]supporting its cost base may involve some difficult decisions following the forthcoming review, but should ultimately leave Ulster 
[normal]Bank 
[normal]as a stronger bank better able to support lending to business.
[normal]&#xa0;
