[normal]              
[normal]Access[bold] to finance, particularly for Small and Medium Enterprises[bold] [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]The Government recognises that access to finance remains a significant challenge for SMEs in 
[normal]Northern Ireland
[normal], as it does across the 
[normal]UK
[normal]. The Northern Ireland Department for 
[normal]Enterprise
[normal], Trade and Investment’s Economic Advisory Group (EAG) produced a detailed report on access to finance in 
[normal]Northern Ireland
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The report included the following conclusions:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The measures set out in our 
[normal]Building a Prosperous and United Community
[normal] package provide a comprehensive framework within which the Government intends to co-ordinate its efforts to boost lending to businesses in 
[normal]Northern Ireland
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal](v)
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal]       [bold]Lack of effectiveness of national initiatives to help aid economic recovery[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]UK
[normal] wide lending schemes set-up by the Government play an important role in providing credit to businesses and individuals in 
[normal]Northern Ireland
[normal]. Ulster Bank 
[normal]has 
[normal]announced that it ha
[normal]s
[normal] approved 
[normal]nearly £8
[normal]0 million of loans through the Funding for Lending Scheme
[normal] (FLS)
[normal], helping 
[normal]over 5
[normal]00 businesses in 
[normal]Northern Ireland
[normal]. FLS has 
[normal]enabled Ulster Bank to establish a new Funding for Lending deal, under which customers will not be charged an arrangement fee for any new loans drawn under the scheme.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The Enterprise Finance Guarantee
[normal] Scheme (EFG) has provided 195
[normal] loans
[normal] amounting to £27.66 million
[normal] 
[normal]in 
[normal]Northern Ireland
[normal] since May 2010
[normal]. 
[normal]In addition to these national schemes, the Northern Ireland Executive has its own £100 million ‘Access to Finance Strategy’, which incorporates a number of smaller schemes designed to boost lending. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]However, the Government accepts that 
[normal]UK
[normal] wide schemes to boost lending have not always been as effective in 
[normal]Northern Ireland
[normal] as they have been elsewhere in the 
[normal]UK
[normal]. The take-up of EFG is lower in 
[normal]Northern Ireland
[normal] than anywhere else in the 
[normal]UK
[normal]. The framework we set out in 
[normal]Building a Prosperous and United Community
[normal] is intended to provide a mechanism to ensure that there is sufficient monitoring and evaluation of national schemes to ensure that they work more effectively in 
[normal]Northern Ireland
[normal] in future.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The package also makes specific proposals on improving existing schemes to increase their impact in 
[normal]Northern Ireland
[normal]. We have fulfilled our commitment in the package to extend the Start-up Loans scheme to 
[normal]Northern Ireland
[normal]. Delivery partners for this scheme have been agreed and the first Start-up Loans have already been made to young entrepreneurs with seven loans approved to the value of £30,000 by the end of October 2013. The package includes a commitment to work to ensure that 
[normal]Northern Ireland
[normal] benefits from a pilot extension to the Enterprise Finance Guarantee Scheme, aimed at addressing loan affordability. We have also committed to continuing to work with the remaining banks to encourage their participation in the Funding for Lending Scheme. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]It is important to note that improving the effectiveness of these schemes cannot be achieved by the Government alone. We would welcome the Committee’s analysis of how banks in 
[normal]Northern Ireland
[normal] are promoting, marketing and championing schemes such as 
[normal]EFG,
[normal] and the extent to which the remaining banks are proactively seeking to address any issues holding them back from joining the Funding for Lending Scheme. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal](vi)
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
